english:
  title: A Reply to the Commander of Haexi
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly submit this response. On the _____ day of this month, your esteemed envoy arrived bearing your gracious letter. I have duly noted that your honored person enjoys ten thousand blessings of good health and fortune. The kindness of your inquiry fills my heart with joy and gratitude beyond what words can express.

    Our sailors and envoys who were previously dispatched to escort our ships have now returned, reporting: "By fortunate circumstance, we arrived within the territory under the command of Your Excellency. Every hardship and misfortune was met with your generous care and protection. Thus we completed our mission safely and returned to our homeland without incident." Upon hearing this account, my gratitude knows no bounds.

    Alas, without the benevolence of a righteous person or noble gentleman—without such deliberate compassion to aid the neighbor and support the weak—how could such kindness ever come to pass?

    Regarding the matter mentioned in the letter from the Mongol Commander: concerning High Goryeo's capture of ships and soldiers from the sea islands—as for the registers of official ranks and numbers that should bear the royal seal—those persons and provisions were hastily gathered from the border towns and dispatched before we could submit a detailed report to the court. Therefore, I must beg your pardon that the specifics could not be properly documented. The border forces were moreover directly escorted by your own officers, so there was no need for us to provide such particular details. All of this arose from our necessity to act swiftly according to circumstances.

    I humbly beseech your bright wisdom to regard this matter favorably and to judge our actions as fitting. The summer heat is oppressive—I only wish that you preserve your health through these warm seasons. Above all, I earnestly hope that you will continue to extend your protection to our small nation. This is my fervent prayer.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This letter is a diplomatic response to a Mongol commander (Yuan officer) regarding the treatment of Goryeo envoys and military personnel, likely written during the period when Goryeo was under Mongol suzerainty.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'sea islands' and captured ships likely concerns military operations along Goryeo's coast, possibly related to piracy or territorial disputes during the Mongol-Yuan period.
